@article{Drew2012,
abstract = {NhaA from Escherichia coli is a prototypical sodium/proton antiporter that regulates pH, cell volume and sodium homeostasis. We have solved the crystal structure of NhaA at 3.5\AA in a novel crystal form in which the protein packs as a physiologically relevant dimer. MD simulations show how the dimer is likely to be positioned in the membrane. A number of conserved charged residues at the centre of the protein are known to be important in the mechanism. Asp163, Asp164 and Asp133 have been suggested as being involved in sodium binding and Asp133 and Lys300 are thought to be important in charge neutralization of a crossover helix assembly. In the new structure we observe the amino group of Lys300 to be located 10\AA from its previously annotated position to lie in exactly the same position as a sodium ion in a structural homologue of NhaA, ASBTNM. Thus, a positive charge at this position is probably an important feature of this structural family. Importantly for NhaA, Lys300 now also forms a salt bridge with Asp163, one of the putative sodium coordinating residues. In molecular dynamics simulations the salt bridge between Lys300 and Asp163 is maintained over a 1 µs time scale unless sodium binds to Asp164, at which point Asp163 reorients to interact with the sodium ion instead. The results suggest a modified model for the transport mechanism of NhaA, in which salt bridges with Lys300 act as electrostatic switches.},
